statistics, and expected life expectancies with disease were calculated from 
knowledge of published survival rates. Management costs were determined from: 
estimates of the installation cost of PET facilities in Canada; management costs 
from our institutions; and recently published Canadian cost estimates of various 
procedures.
RESULTS: A cost savings of 1455 Canadian dollars per person is expected for the 
CT+PET strategy, along with an increase in life expectancy (3.1 days), when 
compared with the CT alone strategy. This cost savings remained in favour of the 
CT+PET strategy when subjected to a rigorous sensitivity analysis.
CONCLUSIONS: PET may be a cost effective means of staging NSCLC in Canada.

