PURPOSE: To identify preferences for and predictors of prognostic information 
among patients with incurable metastatic cancer.
PATIENTS AND METHODS: One hundred twenty-six metastatic cancer patients seeing 
30 oncologists at 12 outpatient clinics in New South Wales, Australia, 
participated in the study. Patients were diagnosed with incurable metastatic 
disease within 6 weeks to 6 months of recruitment. Patients completed a survey 
eliciting their preferences for prognostic information, including type, 
quantity, mode, and timing of presentation; anxiety and depression levels; and 
